<publishercopyright>© 2015 Elsevier B.V.</publishercopyright>
<ce:para>This chapter analyzes new advances in the design of water networks (WNs) based on mathematical optimization and targeting approaches and their application to reduce water consumption in the evolving biofuel industry. Water and energy are two interlinked concepts that need to be addressed simultaneously: water is needed for the production of energy and fuels, and water treatment for its reuse requires energy. Since pinch technology is limited to one contaminant, we highlight WN design for multiple contaminants based on global optimization formulations, as well as the simultaneous optimization, heat and water integration. Next an overview of major biorefinery processes for the production of fuels is given. Finally, the water integration techniques are applied to the design of biofuel production processes that are particularly water-demanding processes, and whose success is directly linked to energy and water consumption. As discussed, this is mostly due to some particularities to low temperature exothermic reactors, and dilute water-based separations that require a large amount of energy and water.</ce:para>
